1. To run an example of 1D random walk on a filament:
   $ ecell3-session 1D.py

2. To view the simulation results wth the Spatiocyte Visualizer:
   $ spatiocyte

3. To create a movie of the simulation results generated by matplotlib (requires avconv preinstalled):
   $ python plot.py

3. To view the movie, we can use the VLC player:
   $ vlc CoordinateLog.csv.mov 

4. To create high quality frames using Blender (warning, this will take a lot of computational time):
   $ blender --background --python blender.py

5. To increase resolution and quality of the rendering, change the following lines in the blender.py:
   bpy.context.scene.render.resolution_percentage = 100
   bpy.context.scene.cycles.samples = 100

6. To create a movie of those frames:
   $ avconv -i image%04d.png -vcodec qtrle blender.mov

7. To run an example of biased 1D random walk on a filament:
   $ ecell3-session 1D_biased_walk.py
